Headline::::
The Sunday trading win was a blip – the weekend is slowly dying




DateTime::::2016-03-10T20:14:39+0000



<p>Monday blues. That Friday feeling. Easy like Sunday mornings.</p>

<p>It’s amazing how we cling to the idea that each day of the week has a distinct personality, even when the myth falls apart under the lightest scientific prodding. People don’t invariably all return to work on Mondays feeling depressed and miserable, for a start. Although that’s perhaps unsurprising, given that for millions Monday isn’t even the beginning of the working week any more, and Sunday mornings are often far from easy.</p>

<p>Children’s lives still divide relatively neatly between five days of school and two of freedom; but for adults the boundaries between working week and weekend are starting to collapse. We live in an increasingly round-the-clock world where work merges with play, and in the case of shift workers at least, nights bleed into days, which soon start to seem much of a muchness.</p>

<p class="pullquote-paragraph">Teenage mall rats now trawl Asos together instead of spending giggly hours in badly lit changing rooms</p>

<p>So the <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/mar/09/cameron-defeated-in-commons-over-plans-to-relax-sunday-trading-laws" title="">government defeat over plans to extend Sunday trading hours</a> felt like a genuine surprise, an almost quaintly countercultural moment – and not just because, for once, Labour got one over the government. George Osborne’s plan to let us all spend longer wandering mindlessly round the shops was thwarted by an unlikely alliance of devout Christians, Tory champions of corner shops (being allowed to open later than the big boys on Sundays gives them a much-needed competitive advantage), Labour MPs rallied by the shop workers’ union USDAW, and the SNP. And so for now we’re all going to Keep Sunday Special, if not in the churchgoing sense then at least in the sense of a day that isn’t just like all the others.</p>

<p>Well, fair enough. Why should shelf-stackers miss Sunday dinner with their families just because some people couldn’t get it together sufficiently to buy a pint of milk during the previous six hours (not to mention six days) that Tesco was actually open? This vote hardly plunges us back to a time when there was nothing to do on the Sabbath but watch tumbleweed blow down the street. In big cities, at least, the shops and cinemas, the pubs and restaurants and theatres, are all open on a Sunday, even if it’s not for quite as long as usual. And nobody ever died of not being able to try on a dress at 9am.</p>

<p>Millions of people already work weekends, of course, without the luxury of politicians intervening to stop it. For nine years as a Sunday newspaper journalist, I was one of them, and the great eye-opener was how many people were doing the same; trudging to the office on a Saturday morning, past wide-eyed clubbers heading home from the night before and mascara-smudged girls doing the walk of shame.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/dec/01/week-amazon-insider-feature-treatment-employees-work">My week as an Amazon insider</a> </p>

<p>And mostly, I didn’t even mind. I was 29 when I started, young enough to change clothes in the office loo at the end of a shift and still catch the end of everyone else’s drunken Saturday night. So what if Monday became the new Sunday? Having a day off when everyone else was working seemed almost luxurious.</p>

<p>But journalists are paid well to do something they love, which is more than can be said for many working antisocial hours. And everything changes once you acquire a spouse, children, and the sudden desire to live in the same time zone as them. Working when everyone else is taking their kids to the park, or prowling round an empty house while they’re at school, doesn’t feel quite so liberating.</p>

<p>So all power to the junior doctors who want recognition for working like this, or the shop workers reluctant to give up their Sunday mornings, or indeed the MPs defending them. But nonetheless, there’s a powerful sense of parliament spitting into the wind. For Sunday opening will probably soon be the least of shop workers’ problems.</p>

<p>Osborne didn’t pick a fight with his own party for no reason; he was responding to big retailers spooked by the threat from online shopping, which can of course be done round the clock in your pyjamas. Lobbyists had argued that letting stores stay open for longer on Sundays might give them more chance to compete, conceivably bringing in another <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://uk.businessinsider.com/osbornes-changes-to-sunday-trading-laws-could-generate-203-billion-2015-7" title="">£20bn in sales over the next two decades </a>– presuming, of course, that the high street actually survives that long.</p>

<p>Because online shopping is eating the bricks-and-mortar behemoths alive. Teenage mall rats now trawl Asos together on their phones instead of spending giggly hours in badly lit changing rooms. Why would they go back to the days of nagging for a lift into town and traipsing round in the rain, when they can press a button on the tablet editions of fashion magazines and “shop the look” instantly?</p>

<p>That’s why public spaces are filling up with services that <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/series/millennials-the-trials-of-generation-y" title="">millennials</a> want but can’t get online – nail bars, hairdressers, gyms, coffee shops – while the surviving stores morph either into places to try before you buy, or into glitzy shop windows for the real operation. Want the skirt you saw on that mannequin? Sure, but we’ll have to order it in for you, from the unglamorous warehouse where the heart of this operation now resides.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/mar/09/cameron-defeated-in-commons-over-plans-to-relax-sunday-trading-laws">No 10 concedes Sunday trading defeat after Commons rebellion</a> </p>

<p>And it’s rather less clear what MPs can do for the invisible army working in those warehouses for online giants such as Amazon, whose management practices were memorably described this week by Management Today magazine’s editor as “<a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-35763908" title="">standing over the rowers with a whip</a>” like something out of Ben Hur. Amazon recently began delivering on Sundays, a logical response to customers moaning about stuff arriving when they were out. They’re just giving us what we say we want. But at a price.</p>

<p>Weekend workers still get weekdays off in lieu, of course. But it’s not quite the same, because there’s something about having your free time at the exact same time everyone else is having theirs that makes a difference.</p>

<p>Sundays off are still for leisurely pub lunches, five-a-side football, family walks, and over-analysing the events of Saturday night with your girlfriends, because that’s when most other people are around. Mondays off are more likely to be spent alone, ticking off errands while answering emails from people who assumed you were in the office.</p>

<p>The slow death of the weekend isn’t just about feeling busier or resentful, but about yet another step away from collective life into a more individualistic, less hidebound but potentially lonelier future. Blue Mondays, indeed.</p>




