I don't buy for a second that poor people, and in particular those who worked the land, were resting on Sundays. And that is beside the point anyway: this author is arguing that the historical tradition of Sundays must be kept. The true historical tradition of Sundays as "rest day" is not "rest day so I can have some time for me and my family away from the grind" but "rest day so I can go to church and devote one day a week to the 'lord' ". That is not a tradition that I personally need to follow, and my guess is that it's not a tradition that this author would like to follow. Moreover, having Sunday trading laws would not prevent people from taking one day per week and devoting it to their God.



